{"title_page": "Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9", "text_new": "{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name    = Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9\n|image   = Malidomacrop.jpg\n|occupation = [[Author]]\n|known_for = Workshops, lectures\n|caption =\n|website = http://www.malidoma.com/\n}}\n\n'''Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9''' (born 1956) is a [[West Africa]]n writer and workshop leader, primarily in the field of spirituality. Born in a [[Dagaaba people|Dagara]] community in Dano, [[Burkina Faso]], he was raised by Jesuits from the age of four. He currently lives on the West Coast of the United States.\n\n==Background==\nAt age four, Som\u00e9 was abducted from his people, the Dagara by a missionary, and taken to a [[boarding school]] where he was inflicted with a Western education.<ref name=\"Wisdom\">{{cite book|last=Som\u00e9|first=Malidoma Patrice|authorlink=Malidoma Patrice Some|title=The Healing Wisdom of Africa|publisher=Tarcher/Putnam|year=1999|location=New York|url=https://archive.org/details/healingwisdomofa00mali/page/1|isbn=0-87477-991-X|pages=[https://archive.org/details/healingwisdomofa00mali/page/1 1\u201315]}}</ref><ref Name=\"Encylopediacom\">{{cite web|title=Som\u00e9, Malidoma Patrice @ Enclyclopedia.com|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2871200066.html|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> Som\u00e9 endured sixteen years of physical and emotional abuse by the priests, but he left the school when he was twenty to return to the village of his birth.<ref Name=\"Encylopediacom\"/><ref name=\"water\">{{cite book|last = Som\u00e9|first = Malidoma Patrice|authorlink = Malidoma Patrice Some|title = Of Water and Spirit: Ritual, Magic and Initiation in the Life of an African Shaman|publisher = Tarcher/Putnam|year = 1994|location = New York|isbn = 978-0-87477-762-8|url = https://archive.org/details/ofwaterspiritrit00som}}</ref>  Upon his return, integration into his [[Traditional African religion|traditional tribal religion]] and customs was difficult, due to his long absence from his culture and his apparent indoctrination into Christianity and a \"white man's world\".<ref name=\"RelAndNat\">{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=Bron|last2=Chester|first2=David|title=Encyclopedia of Religion and Nature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i4mvAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1582#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=A&C Black|accessdate=31 May 2015|year=2008|pages=1581\u20131582|ISBN=978-1847062734}}</ref> Elders from the village believed that Som\u00e9's [[Kinship|ancestral spirit]] had withdrawn from his body and that he had already undergone a type of rite of passage into manhood in the white world.<ref name=\"RelAndNat\"/> Despite this, they agreed to let him undergo a belated manhood rite with a younger group in the tribe. Having been raised outside of the culture and not speaking the language made the month-long, ''baor'' process, believed to unite soul and body, more dangerous for him than for the culturally-Dagara youths also undergoing the rite.<ref name=\"RelAndNat\"/>\n\nSom\u00e9 writes that each person is born with a destiny, and he or she is given a name that reflects that destiny.<ref name=\"water\"/> Som\u00e9 says his name, ''Malidoma'', means \"friend of the enemy/stranger.\"<ref name=\"Wisdom\"/><ref name=\"bio\">\"[http://dickinsg.intrasun.tcnj.edu/diaspora/water.html Biography of Malidoma Patrice Some, Author of Of Water and the Spirit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060511143319/http://dickinsg.intrasun.tcnj.edu/diaspora/water.html |date=2006-05-11 }}\", in ''Religious Traditions of Africa and the African Diaspora'', by the members of Honors AFAM 220 (Spring 1997/ Spring 1999/ Spring 2001).</ref> Som\u00e9 believes it is his destiny to come to Western audiences and promote an understanding between Western and African cultures.<ref name=\"Wisdom\"/>\n\nAfter living in the US for about 10 years, while completing a PhD at [[Brandeis University]], Som\u00e9 went back to Burkina Faso for an arranged marriage to [[Sobonfu Som\u00e9]], a member of the Dagara tribe.<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of Africa: a message... |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/out-of-africa-a-message-1336919.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> They later divorced.<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.soundstrue.com/store/weeklywisdom?page=single&category=IATE&episode=4499\n| title=Invoking Spirit and the Power of Ritual\n| website=Insights at the Edge\n| publisher=Sounds True\n| host=Simon, Tami\n| date=20 September 2011\n| time=\n| access-date=24 Aug 2019\n}}</ref> Sobonfu Som\u00e9 died in 2017.<ref>[http://www.redballoonproject.com/events-grief-ritual-with-sobonfu-some/ Past Events \u2013 Grief Ritual with Sobonfu Som\u00e9 ''Red Balloon Project'']</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSom\u00e9 holds three Master's degrees and two doctorates from the [[Sorbonne]] and [[Brandeis University]].<ref name=\"Wisdom\"/><ref name=\"RelAndNat\"/>\n\nSom\u00e9 currently conducts ''Kontomble'' initiation and [[divination]] retreats and other workshops in the US and Europe.<ref name=\"malidoma\">{{cite web|last=Som\u00e9|first = Malidoma Patrice|authorlink = Malidoma Patrice Some|title = Malidoma.com| year = 2007| url = http://malidoma.com/}}</ref><ref name=\"ECV\">[http://eastcoastvillage.org/main/ Ancestral Wisdom Bridge Foundation]: Som\u00e9's \"Indigenous African Spirit Technologies\" group, with schedule and fees for his events.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Ritual: Power, Healing and Community'', Swan and Raven (1993). {{ISBN|0-14-01-9558-0}}\n* ''Of Water and the Spirit: Ritual, Magic and Initiation in the Life of an African Shaman'', Tarcher/Putnam (1994). {{ISBN|978-0-87477-762-8}}\n* ''The Healing Wisdom of Africa'', Tarcher/Putman (1999). {{ISBN|0-87477-991-X}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web |title=How a West African shaman helped my schizophrenic son in a way Western medicine couldn't |last=Russell |first=Dick |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/03/24/how-a-west-african-shaman-helped-my-schizophrenic-son-in-a-way-western-medicine-couldnt/ |date=24 March 2015 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=31 May 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://eastcoastvillage.org/main/ Ancestral Wisdom Bridge Foundation]: Som\u00e9's \"Indigenous African Spirit Technologies\" group\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060511143319/http://dickinsg.intrasun.tcnj.edu/diaspora/water.html Biography of Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9, author of \"Of Water and the Spirit\"], in ''Religious Traditions of Africa and the African Diaspora''\n* [http://www.elephantjournal.com/2008/04/malidoma-some/ How to Be a Man]: a video interview with Som\u00e9 by elephant journal\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Some, Malidoma Patrice}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Lane County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Religion in the Pacific Northwest]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name    = Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9\n|image   = Malidomacrop.jpg\n|occupation = [[Author]]\n|known_for = Workshops, lectures\n|caption =\n|website = http://www.malidoma.com/\n}}\n\n'''Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9''' (born 1956) is a [[West Africa]]n writer and workshop leader, primarily in the field of spirituality. Born in a [[Dagaaba people|Dagara]] community in Dano, [[Burkina Faso]], he was raised by Jesuits from the age of four. He currently lives on the West Coast of the United States.\n\n==Background==\nAt age four, Som\u00e9 was abducted from his people, the Dagara by a missionary Jesuit priest, and taken to a [[Jesuit]] [[boarding school]] where he was inflicted with a Western education by the priests.<ref name=\"Wisdom\">{{cite book|last=Som\u00e9|first=Malidoma Patrice|authorlink=Malidoma Patrice Some|title=The Healing Wisdom of Africa|publisher=Tarcher/Putnam|year=1999|location=New York|url=https://archive.org/details/healingwisdomofa00mali/page/1|isbn=0-87477-991-X|pages=[https://archive.org/details/healingwisdomofa00mali/page/1 1\u201315]}}</ref><ref Name=\"Encylopediacom\">{{cite web|title=Som\u00e9, Malidoma Patrice @ Enclyclopedia.com|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-2871200066.html|accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> Som\u00e9 endured sixteen years of physical and emotional abuse by the priests, but he left the school when he was twenty to return to the village of his birth.<ref Name=\"Encylopediacom\"/><ref name=\"water\">{{cite book|last = Som\u00e9|first = Malidoma Patrice|authorlink = Malidoma Patrice Some|title = Of Water and Spirit: Ritual, Magic and Initiation in the Life of an African Shaman|publisher = Tarcher/Putnam|year = 1994|location = New York|isbn = 978-0-87477-762-8|url = https://archive.org/details/ofwaterspiritrit00som}}</ref>  Upon his return, integration into his [[Traditional African religion|traditional tribal religion]] and customs was difficult, due to his long absence from his culture and his apparent indoctrination into Christianity and a \"white man's world\".<ref name=\"RelAndNat\">{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=Bron|last2=Chester|first2=David|title=Encyclopedia of Religion and Nature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i4mvAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1582#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=A&C Black|accessdate=31 May 2015|year=2008|pages=1581\u20131582|ISBN=978-1847062734}}</ref> Elders from the village believed that Som\u00e9's [[Kinship|ancestral spirit]] had withdrawn from his body and that he had already undergone a type of rite of passage into manhood in the white world.<ref name=\"RelAndNat\"/> Despite this, they agreed to let him undergo a belated manhood rite with a younger group in the tribe. Having been raised outside of the culture and not speaking the language made the month-long, ''baor'' process, believed to unite soul and body, more dangerous for him than for the culturally-Dagara youths also undergoing the rite.<ref name=\"RelAndNat\"/>\n\nSom\u00e9 writes that each person is born with a destiny, and he or she is given a name that reflects that destiny.<ref name=\"water\"/> Som\u00e9 says his name, ''Malidoma'', means \"friend of the enemy/stranger.\"<ref name=\"Wisdom\"/><ref name=\"bio\">\"[http://dickinsg.intrasun.tcnj.edu/diaspora/water.html Biography of Malidoma Patrice Some, Author of Of Water and the Spirit] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060511143319/http://dickinsg.intrasun.tcnj.edu/diaspora/water.html |date=2006-05-11 }}\", in ''Religious Traditions of Africa and the African Diaspora'', by the members of Honors AFAM 220 (Spring 1997/ Spring 1999/ Spring 2001).</ref> Som\u00e9 believes it is his destiny to come to Western audiences and promote an understanding between Western and African cultures.<ref name=\"Wisdom\"/>\n\nAfter living in the US for about 10 years, while completing a PhD at [[Brandeis University]], Som\u00e9 went back to Burkina Faso for an arranged marriage to [[Sobonfu Som\u00e9]], a member of the Dagara tribe.<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of Africa: a message... |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/out-of-africa-a-message-1336919.html|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> They later divorced.<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.soundstrue.com/store/weeklywisdom?page=single&category=IATE&episode=4499\n| title=Invoking Spirit and the Power of Ritual\n| website=Insights at the Edge\n| publisher=Sounds True\n| host=Simon, Tami\n| date=20 September 2011\n| time=\n| access-date=24 Aug 2019\n}}</ref> Sobonfu Som\u00e9 died in 2017.<ref>[http://www.redballoonproject.com/events-grief-ritual-with-sobonfu-some/ Past Events \u2013 Grief Ritual with Sobonfu Som\u00e9 ''Red Balloon Project'']</ref>\n\n==Education==\nSom\u00e9 holds three Master's degrees and two doctorates from the [[Sorbonne]] and [[Brandeis University]].<ref name=\"Wisdom\"/><ref name=\"RelAndNat\"/>\n\nSom\u00e9 currently conducts ''Kontomble'' initiation and [[divination]] retreats and other workshops in the US and Europe.<ref name=\"malidoma\">{{cite web|last=Som\u00e9|first = Malidoma Patrice|authorlink = Malidoma Patrice Some|title = Malidoma.com| year = 2007| url = http://malidoma.com/}}</ref><ref name=\"ECV\">[http://eastcoastvillage.org/main/ Ancestral Wisdom Bridge Foundation]: Som\u00e9's \"Indigenous African Spirit Technologies\" group, with schedule and fees for his events.</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Ritual: Power, Healing and Community'', Swan and Raven (1993). {{ISBN|0-14-01-9558-0}}\n* ''Of Water and the Spirit: Ritual, Magic and Initiation in the Life of an African Shaman'', Tarcher/Putnam (1994). {{ISBN|978-0-87477-762-8}}\n* ''The Healing Wisdom of Africa'', Tarcher/Putman (1999). {{ISBN|0-87477-991-X}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web |title=How a West African shaman helped my schizophrenic son in a way Western medicine couldn't |last=Russell |first=Dick |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/03/24/how-a-west-african-shaman-helped-my-schizophrenic-son-in-a-way-western-medicine-couldnt/ |date=24 March 2015 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=31 May 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://eastcoastvillage.org/main/ Ancestral Wisdom Bridge Foundation]: Som\u00e9's \"Indigenous African Spirit Technologies\" group\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060511143319/http://dickinsg.intrasun.tcnj.edu/diaspora/water.html Biography of Malidoma Patrice Som\u00e9, author of \"Of Water and the Spirit\"], in ''Religious Traditions of Africa and the African Diaspora''\n* [http://www.elephantjournal.com/2008/04/malidoma-some/ How to Be a Man]: a video interview with Som\u00e9 by elephant journal\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Some, Malidoma Patrice}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Burkinab\u00e9 writers]]\n[[Category:Li